The ships had particu- lar names, as Aquila, Ap0110‚ SpeS, and the like. The flag was square or oblong (vexillam) 3 that of the admiral’s vessel was distinguished by a purple color. The size of the war-ships varied greatly3 the average length of the triremes was perhaps a hun- dred and fifty feet, -breadth, twenty feet. Ships built for quick movement, for inspecting the enemy’s strongholds and harbors, and similar undertakings (naves actuariae), were smaller and lighter. The despatch vessels (naves tabellariae) were very narrow and carried many sails, being provided generally with but one bank of oars. The Roman naval tactics consisted mainly in either propelling a vessel with great force against a rival and crushing the side, or in catching hold of the hostile craft with hookS‚ pulling alongside, springing over on it, and settling the conflict with a hand-to-hand fight. The admiral was called praefectus classis.
